Taiwan Stock Movers: Cheng Uei, Chien Kuo, Epistar, Transcend

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-05-27T05:54:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-27/taiwan-stocks-cheng-uei-chien-kuo-transcend-international.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as 1:30 p.m. close  The Taiex Index rose 21.60, or 0.3 percent, to 8,810. The
benchmark dropped 0.3 percent this week, a second straight week
of losses.  Cheng Uei Precision Industry Co. (2392 TT) gained 3.5
percent to NT$68.50, the steepest increase since May 6. The
maker of connectors, cable assemblies and power packs used in
computers will book a NT$482 million ($17 million) gain from the
sale of 50 million shares in SolLink Inc. to Qualcomm Global
Trading Inc., according to a statement to the Taiwan stock
exchange yesterday.  Chien Kuo Construction Co. (5515 TT) advanced 3.6 percent
to NT$17.40, the biggest gain since May 9. The Taipei-based
construction company plans to sell three mining units in  China 
to TCC Group for NT$1.6 billion, according to a statement to the
stock exchange yesterday. The disposal is estimated to result in
a gain of NT$1.03 billion, Chien Kuo said.  Epistar Corp. (2448)  (2448 TT), the light-emitting diode maker,
surged 5.2 percent to NT$90.50, the largest jump since March 7,
after the Economic Daily News cited an unidentified manager at
the company as saying it got orders from Cree Inc. and Nichia
Corp. Shie-Shien Chang, spokesman for Epistar, didn’t answer
calls to his office.  Transcend Information Inc. (2451)  (2451 TT) advanced 2 percent to
NT$78.60. The dynamic random access memory modules maker plans
to raise employees’ salaries by 10 percent this year, compared
with 3 percent to 5 percent increases in previous years, the
Taipei-based Commercial Times reported, citing Chairman Shu
Chung-Wan. Steve Chang, a spokesman for the company, didn’t
answer calls to his office.  Vanguard International Semiconductor Co. (5347 TT) jumped
4.7 percent to NT$15.70, the steepest jump since Feb. 15, on
speculation second-quarter shipments may exceed estimates, said
William Wang, an analyst at Fubon Securities Co.  The company’s second-quarter shipments may be unchanged
from the previous three months, better than the company’s
forecast of a 1 percent to 3 percent drop, said Wang. K.S.
Chiang, deputy spokesman for Vanguard, declined to comment on
the company’s outlook and said it will give an update at the
next investors’ conference.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Weiyi Lim in Singapore at 
 wlim26@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
